Source and Description¶

Data Source¶

The dataset was sourced from the Open Machine Learning Repository at https://www.openml.org/d/547 (Aldrin, 2004).

The data are a subsample of 500 observations from a data set that originate in a study where air pollution at a road is related to traffic volume and meteorological variables, collected by the Norwegian Public Roads Administration. The response variable consist of hourly values of the logarithm of the concentration of NO2 (particles), measured at Alnabru in Oslo, Norway, between October 2001 and August 2003.

Project Objective¶

The goal of this project is to analyze the predictability of the hourly concentration of nitrogen dioxide particles in the air with a reasonable margin of error using multiple linear regression with just traffic volume and meteorological variables. We also want to determine the variables from the dataset that are actually required for predicting the hourly concentration of nitrogen dioxide.

Statistical modelling of the training data, which predicts the target feature, achieves the goal.

Before modelling, we clean and prepare data, followed by an exploration of dataset features and their inter-relationships.

After modelling, diagnostic checks of the model determine if the model is reliable and if we can predict the target variable using just the given dataset features.

Target Feature¶

Our target feature is Nitrogen Dioxide (NO2) concentration, which is a continuous numerical feature. Hence, our project is on a regression problem.

Descriptive Features¶

The variable descriptions below are from the dataset:

Feature Name Data Type Units Description
no2_concentration continuous particles concentration of nitrogen dioxide
cars_per_hour discrete count number of cars per hour
temperature_at_2m continuous degrees C temperature at 2m above the ground
wind_speed continuous meters/second speed of the wind
temperature_diff_2m_25m continuous degrees C temperature difference between 25m and 2m above the ground
wind_direction discrete degree direction of the wind between 0 and 360
hour_of_day discrete hour the hour of the day between 1 and 24
day discrete count day number from October 1 2001

Backwards Feature Selection¶

We now perform backwards feature selection using p-values.

In [30]:
patsy_desc = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string)
linear_reg_fit = model_full_fitted

#using a 5% significance level
cutoff_for_pval = 0.05 

print(f'''Performing Backwards Feature Selection to obtain a model that only contains significant variables :''')
while True:
    #print(linear_reg_fit.summary())
    pval_series = linear_reg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels = 'Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < cutoff_for_pval):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.5}')
    
    #checking if term is a main effect or interaction term
    if (len(term_components) == 1): 
        patsy_desc.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: 
        patsy_desc.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linear_reg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_desc, data = data).fit()
    
    
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_desc, data = data).fit()

print(f'''\nFit after backwards elimination : 
***{model_reduced_fitted.summary()}***)
Regression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}
Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.5f}
Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.5f}
Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.5f}''')

Summary and Conclusions¶

The full model produced using all the independent variables in our dataset gives a model with an adjusted R-squared value of $48.2\%$. On elimination of two independent variables using the backwards feature selection process we are still able to maintain the same performance with a new adjusted R-squared value of $48.3\%$. The final model thus has 5 variables in total with a p-value equal to zero.

The histogram for residuals of reduced model verifies that the residuals are distributed normally and somewhat symmetrically. This is supported by the scatter plot that shows that the residuals are mostly clustered between $-1.0$ and $1.0$.

The model does not predict any values above approximately $5.5$ particles of Nitrogen Dioxide in the air even when the values are above $6$. The model is otherwise quite consistent in predicting the values of Nitrogen Dioxide concentration with an approximate margin of error, less than $\pm2.0$. The margin of error can be concluded as quite significant given the scale and nature of data to be predicted.

The adjusted r-squared value of the final model however is only $48.3\%$, which is significantly low for the prediction of a physical process. Since the adjusted r-sqaured value measures the explanatory power of the independent variables used in the regression model, we can thus conclude that the meteorological and traffic based variables available in this dataset cannot be used to reliably predict the hourly concentration of nitrogen dioxide in the air using multiple linear regression.
